{"title_page": "Brian Balmages", "text_new": "'''Brian Balmages''' (born January 24, 1975<ref name=change/>) is an [[United States|American]] composer, conductor, and music educator. He is best known for composing wind ensemble works.noob\n\n== Life and career ==\nBrian Balmages was born in [[Baltimore]]. His father was a trumpet player and his mother an opera singer. He obtained a B.A. from [[James Madison University]] and an M.A. from the  [[University of Miami]]. Initially, he played trumpet in the Miami Symphony Orchestra. After finishing his trumpeter career, he concentrated on composition, teaching, music publishing, and on conducting nationwide. Internationally, he has conducted in Canada, Italy, and Australia.\n\nBalmages resides in [[Lutherville, Maryland]].<ref>{{cite newspaper|url=https://www.baltimoresun.com/maryland/baltimore-county/towson/ph-tt-mcgee-column-0718-story.html|newspaper=[[The Baltimore Sun]]|title=Flute choir with strong Towson-area connection readies for Orlando, Fla., performance next month|quote=The program will feature selections by Baltimore composers, including a premiere by Douglas Buchanan, who was commissioned to compose a work to honor the flute choir\u2019s founder; Brian Balmages, a Lutherville-based composer with prominent national recognition, and former Baltimore resident Chris Norman.\n|date=July 18, 2018|access-date=December 29, 2019|first=Courtney|last=McGee}}</ref> He is married and has two children.\n\n==Works==\n=== Wind instruments ===\n* Pele for solo horn and wind ensemble (2004)<ref>{{cite book|title=American Myths, Legends, and Tall Tales: An Encyclopedia of American Folklore|via=[[Google Books]]|editor-first1=Christopher|editor-last1=Fee|editor-first2=Jeffrey|editor-last2=Webb|year=2016|page=775|quote=In 2004, Brian Balmages composed the powerful, haunting Pele for Solo Horn and Wind Ensemble|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kXnEDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA775|access-date=December 28, 2019}}</ref>\n* Moscow 1941 for concert band (2006)<ref>{{Cite newspaper|url=https://marion.wickedlocal.com/news/20191221/old-rochester-regional-junior-high-school-holiday-concert|title=Old Rochester Regional Junior High School Holiday Concert|newspaper=Wicked Local Marion|access-date=December 28, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite newspaper |url=https://www.kenoshanews.com/news/local/band-o-rama-guest-conductor-makes-connections-on-many-levels/article_9e1dcf2f-5edb-5f81-bf32-f0ab2c5287e9.html|title=Band-O-Rama guest conductor makes connections on many levels|first=Terry|last=Flores|newspaper=[[Kenosha News]]|access-date=December 28, 2019}}</ref>\n* Apollo for soprano saxophone and wind ensemble (2008)\n* Summer Resounding! for concert band (2008)<ref>{{Cite newspaper|url=https://lincoln.wickedlocal.com/news/20191209/instrumental-winter-concert-to-take-place-dec-12|title=Instrumental Winter Concert to take place Dec. 12|newspaper=[[Lincoln Journal]]|quote=The concert band will perform \u201cBillboard March\u201d by John Klohr, \u201cAntecedium\u201d by Ed Huckeby, and \u201cSummer Resounding\u201d by Brian Balmages.|date=December 9, 2019|access-date=December 29, 2019}}</ref>\n* Three Celtic Dances for concert band (2008)<ref>{{cite newspaper|date=August 19, 2015|access-date=December 29, 2019|title=An operatic experience|quote=The Junior Band played \u201cThree Celtic Dances\u201d by Brian Balmages comprising The Reel, The Air and The Jig.|url=https://www.youngwitness.com.au/story/3287649/an-operatic-experience/|location=[[Young, New South Wales]]}}</ref>\n* Arabian Dances for symphonic band (2009)\n* Elements for concert band (2010)<ref>{{Cite newspaper|url=https://www.rutlandherald.com/calendar/castleton-university-wind-ensemble/event_439ac17c-f990-11e9-b236-0b1d02e18f00.html|title=Castleton University Wind Ensemble|newspaper=[[Rutland Herald]]|access-date=December 28, 2019}}</ref>\n* Incantation and Ritual for wind orchestra (2015)<ref>{{Cite newspaper|url=https://www.sent-trib.com/community/bobcat-bands-in-concert-tonight/article_76f3ea60-1b5c-11ea-a281-b763cdd00551.html|title=Bobcat bands in concert tonight|date=December 10, 2019|access-date=December 28, 2019|newspaper=Sentinel-Tribune}}</ref>\n* Rippling Watercolors for concert band (2015)<ref>{{Cite newspaper|first=Hannah|last=Johnson|url=https://www.idsnews.com/article/2019/12/out-of-nothing-all-campus-band-showcases-semesters-work-in-concert-tuesday|title=\u2018Out of nothing\u2019: All-Campus Band showcases semester\u2019s work in concert Tuesday|newspaper=[[Indiana Daily Student]]|date=December 11, 2019|access-date=December 28, 2019}}</ref>\n<!--- unsorted --->\n* Into the Arctic<ref>{{Cite newspaper|url=https://www.myeasternshoremd.com/kent_county_news/spotlight/eastern-shore-wind-ensemble-to-let-it-snow-during-winter/article_bb2097cc-b818-570f-8f00-92a62f9d70b0.html|title=Eastern Shore Wind Ensemble to 'Let it Snow' during winter concert|newspaper=[[Kent County News]]|date=December 3, 2019|access-date=December 28, 2019}}</ref>\n* Sapier's Story<ref>{{Cite newspaper|url=http://www.daggerpress.com/2010/05/13/bowden-bel-air-high-school-music-tradition-remains-strong/|title=Bowden: \u201cBel Air High School Music Tradition Remains Strong\u201d|date=May 14, 2010|access-date=December 28, 2019|newspaper=The Dagger}}</ref>\n* Midnight Mission<ref>{{Cite newspaper|url=https://www.clantonadvertiser.com/2018/03/09/224020/|title=CMS students chosen for honor bands|newspaper=The Clanton Advertiser|date=March 9, 2018|access-date=December 28, 2019|quote=\u201cMidnight Mission\u201d by Brian Balmages was Williams\u2019 favorite piece of music from her performance. \u201cDifferent people entered at different times because we were supposed to be secret, and then we had to be silent at times,\u201d Williams said.|first=Joyanna|last=Love}}</ref>\n* Endless Rainbows<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://smnewsnet.com/archives/398072/charles-county-students-participate-in-tri-county-band-chorus-and-orchestra/|title=Charles County Students Participate in Tri-County Band, Chorus and Orchestra|date=January 19, 2016|access-date=December 28, 2019}}</ref>\n* Fanfare Canzonique<ref name=change>{{cite book|title=Winds of Change II - The New Millennium: A Chronicle of the Continuing Evolution of the Contemporary American Wind/Band Ensemble|first=Frank|last=Battisti|publisher=Meredith Music|year=2012|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IipjzEYCRQIC&pg=PT68|page=68|access-date=December 28, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== String instruments ===\n* [[Kyle Woodring#Death|Backstage Pass]] for symphony orchestra, concert band, or jazz band (2015)\n* It Takes One to Tango for cello and orchestra<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://wgxa.tv/news/local/georgia-college-to-host-music-plays-and-festival-in-macon|title=Georgia College to host music, plays, and festival in Macon|first=Amaris|last=Jenkins|date=April 15, 2019|access-date=December 28, 2019|website=[[WGXA]]}}</ref>\n\n== References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.brianbalmages.com/ Musician website]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Balmages, Brian}}\n[[Category:1975 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American trumpeters]]\n[[Category:American conductors (music)]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Baltimore]]\n[[Category:James Madison University alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Miami alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Lutherville, Maryland]]\n[[Category:American music educators]]\n[[Category:19th-century American composers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American composers]]\n", "text_old": "'''Brian Balmages''' (born January 24, 1975<ref name=change/>) is an [[United States|American]] composer, conductor, and music educator. He is best known for composing wind ensemble works. \n\n== Life and career ==\nBrian Balmages was born in [[Baltimore]]. His father was a trumpet player and his mother an opera singer. He obtained a B.A. from [[James Madison University]] and an M.A. from the  [[University of Miami]]. Initially, he played trumpet in the Miami Symphony Orchestra. After finishing his trumpeter career, he concentrated on composition, teaching, music publishing, and on conducting nationwide. Internationally, he has conducted in Canada, Italy, and Australia.\n\nBalmages resides in [[Lutherville, Maryland]].<ref>{{cite newspaper|url=https://www.baltimoresun.com/maryland/baltimore-county/towson/ph-tt-mcgee-column-0718-story.html|newspaper=[[The Baltimore Sun]]|title=Flute choir with strong Towson-area connection readies for Orlando, Fla., performance next month|quote=The program will feature selections by Baltimore composers, including a premiere by Douglas Buchanan, who was commissioned to compose a work to honor the flute choir\u2019s founder; Brian Balmages, a Lutherville-based composer with prominent national recognition, and former Baltimore resident Chris Norman.\n|date=July 18, 2018|access-date=December 29, 2019|first=Courtney|last=McGee}}</ref> He is married and has two children.\n\n==Works==\n=== Wind instruments ===\n* Pele for solo horn and wind ensemble (2004)<ref>{{cite book|title=American Myths, Legends, and Tall Tales: An Encyclopedia of American Folklore|via=[[Google Books]]|editor-first1=Christopher|editor-last1=Fee|editor-first2=Jeffrey|editor-last2=Webb|year=2016|page=775|quote=In 2004, Brian Balmages composed the powerful, haunting Pele for Solo Horn and Wind Ensemble|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kXnEDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA775|access-date=December 28, 2019}}</ref>\n* Moscow 1941 for concert band (2006)<ref>{{Cite newspaper|url=https://marion.wickedlocal.com/news/20191221/old-rochester-regional-junior-high-school-holiday-concert|title=Old Rochester Regional Junior High School Holiday Concert|newspaper=Wicked Local Marion|access-date=December 28, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite newspaper |url=https://www.kenoshanews.com/news/local/band-o-rama-guest-conductor-makes-connections-on-many-levels/article_9e1dcf2f-5edb-5f81-bf32-f0ab2c5287e9.html|title=Band-O-Rama guest conductor makes connections on many levels|first=Terry|last=Flores|news