ory:Bipolar disorder in fiction]]\n[[Category:Mental illness in fiction]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Lesbian-related television programs]]\n[[Category:Fox Broadcasting Company original programming]]\n[[Category:Hip hop television]]\n[[Category:Serial drama television series]]\n[[Category:Television series based on plays]]\n[[Category:Television series about dysfunctional families]]\n[[Category:Television series by 20th Century Fox Television]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in New York City]]\n[[Category:New York City in fiction]]\n[[Category:Television shows featuring audio description]]\n[[Category:2010s American black television series]]\n[[Category:American black television series]]\n[[Category:Television series created by Lee Daniels]]\n", "text_old": "{{other uses2|Empire}}\n{{short description|2015 American television series}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = Empire\n| image                    = Empire Intertitle.png\n| genre                    = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Musical film|Musical]]<br /> [[Drama (film and television)|Drama]]\n}}\n| creator                  = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Lee Daniels]]\n* [[Danny Strong]]\n}}\n| starring                 = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Terrence Howard]]\n* [[Taraji P. Henson]]\n* [[Bryshere Y. Gray]]\n* [[Jussie Smollett]]\n* [[Trai Byers]]\n* [[Grace Byers]]\n* [[Malik Yoba]]\n* [[Kaitlin Doubleday]]\n* [[Gabourey Sidibe]]\n* [[Ta'Rhonda Jones]]\n* [[Serayah (actress)|Serayah]]\n* [[Morocco Omari]]\n* [[Xzibit]]\n* [[Bre-Z]]\n* [[Rumer Willis]]\n* Terrell Carter\n* [[Andre Royo]]\n* [[Nicole Ari Parker]]\n* Chet Hanks\n* [[Rhyon Nicole Brown]]\n* A. Z. Kelsey \n* [[Vivica A. Fox]]\n* [[Meta Golding]]\n* [[Mario (American entertainer)|Mario]]\n* Katlynn Simone\n* [[Wood Harris]]\n* \n}}\n| composer                 = {{Plainlist|\n* Fil Eisler (score)\n* [[Rodney Jerkins]], [[Ester Dean]], [[Jim Beanz]], et al<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.empireboobookitty.com/2015/11/jim-beanz-empires-musical-mastermind.html |title=Jim Beanz, Empire's Musical Mastermind|date=May 1, 2017 |work=Empire BBK |access-date=May 1, 2017}}</ref> (songs)\n}}\n| country                  = United States\n| language                 = English\n| num_seasons              = 6 \n| num_episodes             = 99\n| list_episodes            = List of Empire episodes\n| executive_producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* Danny Strong\n* [[Brian Grazer]]\n* [[Robert Munic]]\n* Francie Calfo\n* [[Ilene Chaiken]]\n* [[Sanaa Hamri]]\n* Lee Daniels\n* Dennis Hammer\n* Brent Mahoney\n}}\n| producer                 = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Attica Locke]]\n* Malcolm Spellman\n* [[Loucas George]]\n* Dianne Houston\n* Craig Brewer (co-executive producer) \n}}\n| location                 = [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]]<br />[[New York City]]<br />[[Philadelphia]], [[Pennsylvania]]\n| cinematography           = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Andrew Dunn (cinematographer)|Andrew Dunn]]\n*Paul M. Sommers\n}}\n| editor                   = {{Plainlist|\n*Joe Leonard\n*Zack Arnold\n*Ra\u00fal D\u00e1valos\n*Natalie A. Boschan\n*Matt Barber\n}}\n| runtime                  = 42 minutes\n| company                  = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Imagine Entertainment|Imagine Television]]\n* [[Lee Daniels|Lee Daniels Entertainment]]\n* [[Danny Strong|Danny Strong Productions]]\n* Little Chicken Inc.<br>(2015-2018)<br>(seasons 1-4)\n* [[20th Century Fox Television]]\n}}\n| distributor              = [[20th Television]]\n| network                  = [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]]\n| picture_format           = [[1080i]] ([[High-definition television|HDTV]])\n| first_aired              = {{Start date|2015|1|7}}\n| last_aired               = {{End date|present}}\n| related                  = <!-- To be used >>>only<<< for remakes, spin-offs, and adaptations -->\n| website                  = https://www.fox.com/empire/\n| image_alt                = \n| caption                  = \n| first_run                = \n| released                 = \n| channel                  = \n}}\n\n'''''Empire''''' is an American musical [[television drama|drama]] television series created by [[Lee Daniels]] and [[Danny Strong]] for [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]]. It is a joint production by [[Imagine Television]] and [[20th Century Fox Television]] and syndicated by [[20th Television]]. Although it is filmed in [[Chicago]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt3228904/locations |title=Empire |date=January 7, 2015 \u2013 December 17, 2019|website=IMDb |accessdate=July 27, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2015/feb/06/empire-economy-fox-drama-chicago|title='The Empire economy': how the hit Fox show is making Chicago swing|first=Britt|last=Julious|date=February 6, 2015|work=[[The Guardian]] |location=London  |accessdate=July 27, 2016}}</ref> the show is set in [[New York City|New York]]. The series centers on the fictional [[hip hop music]] and [[entertainment]] company Empire Entertainment, and the drama among the members of the founders' family as they fight for control of it.\n\nThe pilot was a success, garnering praise for [[Taraji P. Henson]]'s portrayal of Cookie Lyon. The series premiered on January 7, 2015 to nearly 10 million viewers while the first-season finale was watched by 17 million viewers.\n\nOn April 30, 2019, Fox renewed the show for a sixth and final season. It premiered on September 24, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/04/empire-renewed-for-season-6-jussie-smollett-future-1202604910/|title=\u2018Empire\u2019 Renewed For Season 6 By Fox; \"No Plans\" For Jussie Smollett\u2019s Role To Return, Yet|last=Patten|first=Dominic|work=Deadline Hollywood|date=April 30, 2018|accessdate=April 30, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tvguide.com/news/empire-ending-season-6-fox/|title=''Empire'' to End After Season 6|publisher=TVGuide.com|first=Amanda|last=Bell|date=May 13, 2019|accessdate=May 13, 2019}}</ref><ref>[https://www.dailywire.com/news/48324/empire-creator-blames-hate-crime-hoaxer-jussie-paul-bois]</ref><ref name=\"S6PremiereDate\">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/06/fox-sets-fall-premiere-dates-emmys-9-1-1-the-masked-singer-empire-more-1202637086/|title=Fox Sets Fall Premiere Dates: Emmys Kick Off The Week, '9-1-1', 'The Masked Singer', 'Empire', More|work=Deadline Hollywood|first=Denise|last=Petski|date=June 24, 2019|accessdate=June 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Premise==\n[[Lucious Lyon]] ([[Terrence Howard]]) is a hip hop mogul, former drug dealer, and CEO of Empire Entertainment. Informed of his own imminent early death from a certain medical condition, Lucious is forced to choose from amongst his progeny, a successor who will control his dynasty after his demise. He begins working to groom one of his three sons to take over the family business \u2013 Empire CFO [[Andre Lyon (Empire)|Andre]] ([[Trai Byers]]), R&B singer-songwriter [[Jamal Lyon|Jamal]] ([[Jussie Smollett]]), and rapper [[Hakeem Lyon|Hakeem]] ([[Bryshere Y. Gray]]). In the process, Lucious pits them against each other.<ref name=\"Lee and Howard\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cinemablend.com/television/Terrence-Howard-Rules-Hip-Hop-Family-Fox-Empire-Trailer-64018.html|title=Terrence Howard Rules Hip Hop And Family In Fox's Empire Trailer|work=cinemablend.com|last=West|first=Kelly|date=July 9, 2014|accessdate=July 9, 2015}}</ref> Lucious' ex-wife [[Cookie Lyon]] ([[Taraji P. Henson]]) is released from prison after serving a 17-year sentence, and also pulls for control of both the company and of her sons.\n\n==Cast and characters==\n{{Main|List of Empire characters}}\n*[[Terrence Howard]] as [[Lucious Lyon|Lucious Lyon, n\u00e9 Dwight Walker]]\n: A former drug dealer turned hip-hop mogul and the founder and long-time CEO of Empire Entertainment,<ref name=\"HowardCasting\"/> his life begins to cave in around him after his past sins come back to haunt him when he is diagnosed with [[amyotrophic lateral sclerosis]].\n*[[Taraji P. Henson]] as [[Cookie Lyon|Loretha \"Cookie\" Lyon, n\u00e9e Holloway]]\n: Lucious' outspoken wife and mother of his three sons. She serves a 17-year prison sentence for [[drug dealing]] and sees herself as the sacrificial lamb for Empire Entertainment, which she built with Lucious, but then took the fall for him while running the very drugs that financed Lucious' early career. Upon her return from prison, she is determined to bring the Lyon family back together and reclaim her share of Empire Entertainment.<ref name=TPHNFLiFLDHDE/><ref>{{cite web |title=Everything You Need to Know About 'Empire,' TV's Most Talked-About New Show!|url=http://www.etonline.com/tv/157052_everything_you_need_to_know_about_empire_tv_s_most_talked_about_new_show/ |first=Meredith B. |last=Kile |date=January 28, 2015 |publisher=[[Entertainment Tonight|ET Online]] |accessdate=March 25, 2015 }}</ref> In the second season, Cookie leaves the Empire group and starts her own record label, Lyon Dynasty. After allowing Empire Entertainment to acquire Lyon Dynasty, she returns to Empire as co-CEO and Head of [[A&R]].\n*[[Bryshere Y. Gray]] as [[Hakeem Lyon]]\n: Lucious' fame-obsessed youngest son and his favorite child, who is a hip hop star on the rise.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2014/03/ryan-mcpartlin-joins-nbc-pilot-salvation-bryshere-y-gray-cast-in-foxs-empire-694998/ |title=Ryan McPartlin Joins NBC Pilot 'Salvation'; Bryshere Y. Gray Cast In Fox's 'Empire' |date=March 6, 2014 |accessdate=January 2, 2015 |first=Nellie|last=Andreeva |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]}}</ref> Initially combative towards his mother Cookie, Hakeem starts to become friendlier towards her, and has a great relationship with his older brother Jamal. He has had romantic relationships with Tiana, Camilla, Anika, Valentina, and Laura.\n*[[Jussie Smollett]] as [[Jamal Lyon]] (seasons 1\u20135)\n: The middle son of the Lyon family, he is a talented gay singer-songwriter who despises the corporate aspect of the music industry. Jamal is estranged from his father, who considers him the [[black sheep]] of the family.<ref name=TPHNFLiFLDHDE/> Jamal is Cookie's favorite and has a strong relationship with his brother Hakeem. Lucious appoints Jamal as his successor at the end of the first season, and later as interim CEO when Lucious is arrested. Jamal later relinquishes control of Empire back to Lucious. After being accidentally shot by Freda Gatz in Season 2, Jamal begins to present symptoms of PTSD and a reliance on painkillers. His addiction ultimately leads to a visit to rehab. Smollet's character was removed from the last two episodes of the fifth season after Smollett was indicted on charges of staging an assault against himself.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Whitten |first1=Sarah |title=Empire producers remove Jussie Smollett from final episodes of season |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/02/22/twentieth-century-fox-television-says-it-is-removing-jussie-smolletts-character-from-final-two-episodes-of-empire.html |website=www.cnbc.com |date=22 February 2019}}</ref> Smollett's character does not return for the sixth and final season but he is heavily mentioned.\n*[[Trai Byers]] as [[Andre Lyon (Empire)|Andre Lyon]]\n: The eldest son of the Lyon family<ref name=GSRWLDoFE/> and [[CFO]] of Empire Entertainment. He is [[Wharton School of Business|Wharton]] educated, power hungry, and has [[bipolar disorder]]. He is married to his college sweetheart, Rhonda. He plans to run Empire, but is in a battle for the head chair with his younger brothers. In the second season, Andre initially helps Cookie and Hakeem set up Lyon Dynasty, but returns to Empire. Lucious later promotes Andre to President of Gutter Life Records, a sub-division of Empire Entertainment consisting of mainly urban rappers, such as Freda Gatz. In Season 3, 4 & 5, he loses his wife and becomes involved with Nessa, Charlotte, Pamela and Teri (the latter who becomes his new wife in the season 5 finale). \n*[[Grace Gealey|Grace Byers]] as Anika \"Boo Boo Kitty\" Calhoun (seasons 1\u20134) \n: Initially the ambitious head of Empire Entertainment's [[A&R]] department,<ref name=GSRWLDoFE/> she becomes engaged to Lucious though they will eventually separate. After leaving Empire, Anika has sex with Hakeem and becomes pregnant. Fearful of Rhonda's pregnancy, as Rhonda's unborn child has claim to being the heir of Empire, Anika pushes Rhonda down a set of stairs, leading to the death of Rhonda's unborn child. Cookie and Anika share an extreme dislike for one another, with Cookie referring to Anika by the derisive nickname \"[[Laverne & Shirley|Boo Boo Kitty]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ew.com/article/2015/03/02/empire-star-taraji-p-henson-her-signature-line-you-don%E2%80%99t-want-be-called-boo-boo|title=Empire star Taraji P. Henson on her signature line: 'You don't want to be called Boo Boo Kitty' | last=Stack |first=Tim | date=March 2, 2015 |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |accessdate=March 5, 2015}}</ref> She dies in the season 4 finale.\n*[[Malik Yoba]] as Vernon Turner (season 1)\n: Lucious's longtime friend and business partner, and chairman of Empire Entertainment. In the season one finale, Vernon is struck and killed by Rhonda, when he attacks Andre, and both end up hiding the body.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2014/03/malik-yoba-joins-fox-drama-pilot-empire-695848/ |title=Malik Yoba Joins Fox Drama Pilot 'Empire' |date=March 7, 2014 |first=Nellie |last=Andreeva |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |accessdate=January 2, 2015}}</ref>\n*[[Kaitlin Doubleday]] as Rhonda Lyon (seasons 1\u20132; recurring in season 3; guest in season 4)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2014/03/kaitlin-doubleday-joins-fox-drama-pilot-empire-regina-hall-in-fxs-married-697294/ |title=Kaitlin Doubleday Joins Fox Drama Pilot 'Empire'; Regina Hall In FX's 'Married' |date=March 11, 2014 |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |accessdate=January 2, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://theurbandaily.com/2014/10/28/chris-powell-empire-tv-show/|title=Comedian CP (Chris Powell) Lands Role In Lee Daniels' \"Empire\" [EXCLUSIVE VIDEO] |work=theurbandaily.com|date=October 28, 2014|accessdate=February 11, 2015}}</ref>\n: Andre's wife is a \"[[ride-or-die chick]]\" who is extremely fierce and loyal, and sticks by Andre's side as he tries to gain control of Empire. In the first-season finale she finds out that she is pregnant, but Anika pushes her down the stairs in the second season fall finale, and the baby dies in the second-season spring premiere. After her recovery, Rhonda begins to work for Empire's fashion label, \"Antony and Cleopatra\", initially run by Camilla Marks-Whiteman. After Camilla's suicide, Rhonda is appointed Creative Director of Antony and Cleopatra. In the third-season premiere, she attacks Anika due to finding out Anika had pushed her down the stairs earlier in the season, causing her to lose her unborn son. As a result, she falls off the building she and Anika were fighting on, lands on a car, and dies. She makes numerous appearances to Andre as a ghost during his hallucinations in the third season.\n*[[Ta'Rhonda Jones]] as Porsha Taylor (season 2\u20136; recurring in season 1)\n: Cookie's executive assistant.\n*[[Gabourey Sidibe]] as Rebecca \"Becky\" Williams (season 2\u20136; recurring in season 1)\n: Executive assistant to Lucious at Empire Entertainment. After Jamal's promotion to Vice Chairman, Jamal promotes Becky to A&R at Empire and its sub-label, Gutter Life Records. In season 4, she had taken Anika's position as Head of A&R requested by Cookie.<ref name=GSRWLDoFE/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2014/03/gabourey-sidibe-joins-fox-drama-pilot-empire-andrew-lees-in-tbs-your-family-or-mine-696557/ |title=Gabourey Sidibe & 2 More Join Fox Pilot 'Empire'; Andrew Lees In TBS' 'Your Family Or Mine' |date=March 10, 2014 |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |accessdate=January 2, 2015}}</ref>\n*[[Serayah (actress)|Serayah]] as Tiana Brown\u2013Lyon (seasons 2\u20136; recurring in season 1)\n: An artist at Empire Entertainment who becomes Hakeem's girlfriend for some time.<ref name=McNeill>{{cite web|url=http://tvline.com/2015/08/26/empire-serayah-series-regular-season-2/|title=Empire Promotes Serayah for Season 2|accessdate=September 10, 2015|first=Kimberly|last=Roots|date=August 26, 2015|work=[[TVLine]]|publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]]}}</ref> In season two, she leaves Empire for Lyon Dynasty. She also starts to get jealous of the relationship Hakeem has with Laura. In Season 3, she and Hakeem rekindle their relationship. At the beginning of Season 4 she remains happy being with Hakeem and looks after his daughter Bella whilst Anika is in jail. Halfway through the season she gets manipulated by Eddie Barker and turns down a proposal made by Hakeem. She continues to be manipulated by Eddie and becomes Empire's number one artist. After Hakeem tries to warn her about Eddie she breaks up with him again, but they quickly get back together after Tiana reveals to Hakeem that she's pregnant. Tiana's lovers were Gram (season 3) and Devon (season 5&mdash;6).\n*[[Bre-Z]] as Freda Gathers/\"Freda Gatz\" (season 3; recurring in season 2)\n: A female rapper, who becomes a surrogate daughter to Lucious after the murder of her father, Frank Gathers. Lucious later sets up Freda to become Hakeem's rival.\n*[[Morocco Omari]] as Tariq Cousins (season 3; recurring in season 2)\n: An [[Federal Bureau of Investigation|FBI]] Agent, who is also Lucious' half-brother.<ref>{{cite web|last=Slezak |first=Michael |url=http://tvline.com/2016/02/05/empire-season-2-cast-morocco-omari-fbi-agent/ |title=\u2018Empire\u2019 Season 2 Casts Morocco Omari as FBI Agent |website=TVLine.com |date=2016-02-05 |accessdate=2017-01-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://2paragraphs.com/2016/09/who-is-lucious-half-brother-tariq-on-empire/amp/ |title=Who Is Lucious\u2019 Half-Brother Tariq on \u2018Empire\u2019? \u2013 |website=2paragraphs.com |date= |accessdate=2017-01-26}}</ref>\n*[[Xzibit]] as Leslie \"Shyne\" Johnson (season 3\u20134; guest in season 2)\n: A former rival of [[Lucious Lyon]] that soon becomes a close ally, described as \"100 percent wolf and 100 percent gangsta\".\n*[[Andre Royo]] as Thurston \"Thirsty\" Rawlings, (seasons 4\u20135; seasons 2\u22123 recurring)\n: Lucious' lawyer/confidant/right-hand man.\n*[[Rumer Willis]] as Tory Ash, (season 4; season 3 guest) \n:A singer who fell off as an addict than becomes close friends with Jamal to betray him by working with Lucious.\n*Terrell Carter as Warren Hall, (season 4) \n:An attorney, Diana Dubois' nephew, Angelo's cousin and Jamal's ex.\n*[[Nicole Ari Parker]] as Giselle Sims-Barker, (season 5\u20136; season 4 recurring) \n: Eddie Barker\u2019s trophy ex-wife.\n*Chet Hanks as Blake Sterling, (season 5; season 4 recurring) \n:A rapper and Hakeem's friend.\n*[[Rhyon Nicole Brown]] as Maya (seasons 5\u20136; season 4 recurring)\n:The daughter of Cookie's fellow inmate Poundcake.\n*A.Z. Kelsey as Jeff Kingsley (seasons 5\u20136)\n:Hotshot, Silicon Valley genius turned interim leader of Empire Entertainment. He is Ivy League educated with an edge and a dark secret. Lucious' illegitimate son. In the season five finale, Jeff commits suicide in front of Lucious, and his heart is given to Andre for a heart transplant.\n*[[Vivica A. Fox]] as Candace Holloway Mason (season 6; seasons 2-5 recurring)\n:Cookie's well-behaved but snobby and judgmental older sister. She is a [[realtor]].\n*[[Mario (American entertainer)|Mario]] as Devon (season 6; season 5 recurring): Lucious' new artist and Tiana\u2019s new love interest. \n*[[Meta Golding]] as Teri Lyon (season 6; season 5 recurring)\n:Andre\u2019s new wife and Quincy's mother. \n*Katlynn Simone as Treasure (season 6; season 5 recurring)\n:Formerly a prison social worker, but now an artist at Empire and Tiana\u2019s main rival.\n*[[Wood Harris]] as Damon Cross (season 6; season 5 recurring)\n:Lucious' rival and Cookie's new love interest.\n\n==Episodes==<!-- To edit the table in this section, you need to edit the \"Season overview\" table in [[List of Empire episodes]] -->\n{{main|List of Empire episodes}}\n{{:List of Empire episodes}}\n\n==Production==\n[[File:\"VOICE AWARDS-2015\" (21409573660).jpg|thumb|left|Joshua Allen and Attica Locke, writers and producers of the show Empire, stand with their 2015 Voice Award. They are joined by Sonay Washington Hoffman from Writers Guild of America, West.]]\nHoward, Henson and Sidibe filmed the [[pilot episode]] in [[Chicago]] (Cinespace Chicago Film Studios<ref>https://www.chicagofilmstudios.com/credits</ref>) in March 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2014-05-07/entertainment/chi-lee-daniels-empire-chicago-fox-20140507_1_lee-daniels-francie-calfo-the-butler|title=Lee Daniels' 'Empire' picked up by Fox, will 'likely' film in Chicago|accessdate=May 12, 2014|date=May 7, 2014|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|last=Gomez|first=Luis}}</ref> On May 6, 2014, [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] picked up ''Empire'' as a series order for its [[2014\u201315 United States network television schedule|2014\u201315 television schedule]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://insidetv.ew.com/2014/05/06/foxs-hip-hop-drama-empire-gets-series-order/|title=Lee Daniels hip-hop drama 'Empire' gets Fox series order|accessdate=May 12, 2014|date=May 6, 2014|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|last=Hibberd|first= James}}</ref><ref name=\"Braxton\">{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/tv/showtracker/la-et-st-lee-daniels-empire-fox-terrence-howard-20140506-story.html|title=Lee Daniels' 'Empire,' starring Terrence Howard, headed for Fox |accessdate=May 12, 2014|date=May 6, 2014|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|last=Braxton|first=Greg}}</ref> On May 12, 2014, Fox announced that ''Empire'' would air as a midseason replacement, rather than as a part of the fall schedule.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2014/05/12/fox-2014-15-schedule-announced-gotham-mondays-bones-shifts-to-thursday-brooklyn-nine-nine-joins-sunday/262992/|title=Fox 2014\u201315 Schedule Announced: 'Gotham' & 'Sleepy Hollow' Monday, 'Bones' Shifts to Thursday & 'Brooklyn Nine-Nine' Joins Sunday With 'Mulaney' + 'Glee' Held for Midseason|publisher=Tribune Digital Ventures|accessdate=October 28, 2014|date=May 12, 2014|work=TV by the Numbers|last=Kondolojy|first= Amanda}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|title=Fox 2014 Schedule: 'Brooklyn Nine-Nine' & 'Mulaney' Join Sunday Animated Block, 'Glee' Held For Midseason|url=https://www.deadline.com/2014/05/fox-fall-schedule-2014-upfronts-new-shows/|accessdate=May 12, 2014|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=May 12, 2014}}</ref> On November 19, 2014, it was confirmed that the [[Pilot (Empire)|pilot episode]] would premiere on January 7, 2015, following the [[American Idol (season 14)|season 14]] premiere of ''[[American Idol]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/foxs-empire-nabs-post-american-749190|title=Fox's 'Empire' Nabs Post-'American Idol' Slot: It's not immediately clear what the new Wednesday means for current occupant 'Red Band Society'|accessdate=November 20, 2014|date=November 19, 2014|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|last=O'Connell|first= Michael}}</ref>\n\nThe [[executive producer]]s are [[Brian Grazer]], [[Danny Strong]] and Francie Calfo. The show is written by Strong while [[Lee Daniels]], who has been nominated for the [[Academy Award for Best Director]], made his television directorial debut with the show.<ref name=GSRWLDoFE/><ref name=\"LeeDanielsDynasty\">{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/lee-daniels-foxs-empire-i-701855|title=Lee Daniels on Fox's 'Empire': 'I Wanted to Make a Black 'Dynasty' ' (Q&A)|accessdate=December 14, 2014|date=May 6, 2014|last=Wilson|first=Stacey|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|publisher=Prometheus Global Media}}</ref> According to Strong, the show is based in part on [[William Shakespeare]]'s ''[[King Lear]]'', and James Goldman's ''[[The Lion in Winter]]''; Daniels also acknowledged a strong influence from the [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] prime-time [[soap opera]] ''[[Dynasty (1981 TV series)|Dynasty]]''.<ref name=\"LeeDanielsDynasty\" /><ref name=EWStack010715/> [[Ilene Chaiken]] later joined the series as [[showrunner]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2014/05/ilene-chaiken-empire-showrunner-fox-729943/|title=Ilene Chaiken Boards New Fox Series 'Empire' As Showrunner|first=Nellie|last=Andreeva|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=\nMay 13, 2014|access-date=January 8, 2015}}</ref>\nOn January 17, 2015, the series was renewed for an 18-episode [[Empire (season 2)|second season]],<ref name=\"Fox Renewals 2015\">{{cite web|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2015/01/17/gotham-brooklyn-nine-nine-empire-renewed-for-new-seasons-by-fox/351484/|title='Gotham', 'Brooklyn Nine-Nine' & 'Empire' Renewed for new seasons by FOX|last=Kondolojy|first=Amanda|work=TV by the Numbers|publisher=Tribune Digital Ventures|date=January 17, 2015|accessdate=January 17, 2015}}</ref> which premiered on September 23, 2015.<ref name=\"Neyo2\">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2015/05/empire-season-2-episode-number-ne-yo-american-idol-judges-final-season-1201424356/|title='Empire' Season 2 Episode Number Set, Ne-Yo Joins as Music Producer, Former 'Idol' Judges May Appear on Final Season|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=May 11, 2015|accessdate=May 12, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Empire (season 4)|fourth season]], consisting of eighteen episodes premiered on September 27, 2017, and crossed over with another Fox series co-created by Daniels, ''[[Star (TV series)|Star]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://tvline.com/2017/07/12/empire-star-crossover-cookie-carlotta-video/|title=Empire/Star Crossover Confirmed \u2014 It's Cookie vs. Carlotta (Watch Teaser)|last=Ausiello|first=Michael|work=TVLine|date=July 12, 2017|accessdate=July 12, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2017/01/empire-renewed-season-4-fox-tca-1201883228/|title=\u2018Empire\u2019 Renewed For Season 4 By Fox|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|date=January 11, 2017|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|accessdate=January 11, 2017}}</ref> \n\nOn May 2, 2018, Fox renewed the series for a [[Empire (season 5)|fifth season]] with Brett Mahoney taking over as showrunner from [[Ilene Chaiken]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/05/empire-renewed-season-5-fox-brett-mahoney-showrunner-1202381308/|title=\u2018Empire\u2019 Renewed For Season 5 By Fox With Brett Mahoney As Showrunner|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=May 2, 2018|accessdate=May 3, 2018}}</ref> The season premiered on September 26, 2018.<ref name=\"5thpremiere\">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/06/fox-fall-premiere-dates-2018-empire-9-1-1-lethal-weapon-last-man-standing-nfl-1202418890/|title=Fox Sets Fall Premiere Dates: 'Empire', '9-1-1', Recast 'Lethal Weapon' & More|last=Pedersen|first=Erik|work=Deadline Hollywood|date=June 28, 2018|accessdate=June 28, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn April 15, 2019, ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' reported that a judge was allowing 300 jailed youth to sue Fox for using their prison facility to film ''Empire.''<ref name=2019_Sue>https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/thr-esq/judge-asked-let-300-jailed-kids-sue-filming-foxs-empire-at-youth-detention-center-1202178</ref>\n\nIn March 2020, production of the final season was shut down due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2020/film/news/films-tv-delayed-coronavirus-canceled-1203532033/|title=All the Shows and Movies Shut Down or Delayed Because of Coronavirus|last=Thorne|first=Will|last2=Aurthur|first2=Kate|date=2020-03-12|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref>\n\n===Casting===\nHoward was cast in the lead on February 19, 2014.<ref name=\"HowardCasting\">{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/terrence-howard-star-foxs-lee-676817|title=Terrence Howard to Star in Fox's Lee Daniels Hip-Hop Drama|accessdate=October 28, 2014|date=February 19, 2014|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|first1=Lesley|last1=Goldberg|first2=Philiana|last2=Ng}}</ref> Henson was named as the female lead on February 26, and [[Jussie Smollett]] was announced in a starring role.<ref name=TPHNFLiFLDHDE>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/taraji-p-henson-nabs-female-683622|title=Taraji P. Henson Nabs Female Lead in Fox's Lee Daniels Hip-Hop Drama 'Empire'|accessdate=October 28, 2014|date=February 26, 2014|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|last=Goldberg|first= Lesley}}</ref> Howard and Henson previously starred together as love interests in the film ''[[Hustle & Flow]]'', and starred in the 2005 film ''[[Four Brothers (film)|Four Brothers]]''.<ref name=TPHNFLiFLDHDE/> On March 10, 2014, Sidibe, who had previously worked with Daniels in ''[[Precious (film)|Precious]]'', was cast in a recurring role as Becky, Lucious' assistant. [[Trai Byers]] and [[Grace Gealey]] were announced in regular roles, while [[Bryshere Y. Gray]] and [[Malik Yoba]] were announced in starring roles.<ref name=GSRWLDoFE>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/gabourey-sidibe-reunites-lee-daniels-687238|title=Gabourey Sidibe Reunites With Lee Daniels on Fox's 'Empire'|accessdate=October 28, 2014|date=March 10, 2014|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|last=Goldberg|first=Lesley}}</ref> [[Courtney Love]] was added to the cast on October 23, 2014.<ref name=\"CLJEPJ2oF\">{{cite web|url=http://www.broadwayworld.com/bwwtv/article/Courtney-Love-Joins-EMPIRE-Premiering-January-2015-on-FOX-20141023|title=Courtney Love Joins EMPIRE, Premiering January 2015 on FOX|accessdate=October 28, 2014|date=October 23, 2014|website=BroadwayWorld.com}}</ref> [[Naomi Campbell]] was announced in a recurring role on September 29, 2014.<ref name=\"CampbellCasting\">{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/naomi-campbell-joins-lee-daniels-735992|title=Naomi Campbell Joins Lee Daniels' Fox Hip-Hop Drama 'Empire' (Exclusive)|accessdate=November 19, 2014|date=September 29, 2014|last=Goldberg|first=Lesley|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]}}</ref>\n\nOn June 2, 2015, it was announced [[Adam Rodriguez]] would join the cast in a recurring role in the second season of ''Empire'', portraying Laz Delgado, a potential love interest for Cookie.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://tvline.com/2015/06/02/empire-adam-rodriguez-season-2-cast-cookie-boyfriend/|title=''Empire'' Season 2: Adam Rodriguez to Recur \u2014 and Woo Cookie? |work=TVLine |first=Michael |last=Slezak |date=June 2, 2015 |accessdate=June 2, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, [[Phylicia Rashad]] was cast as a recurring guest star in the role of Diana DuBois in the third season of ''Empire''.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://variety.com/2016/tv/news/phylicia-rashad-empire-season-3-cast-diana-dubois-1201846559/|title=\u2018Empire\u2019 Season 3 Guest Stars: Phylicia Rashad Joins Mariah Carey & More|last=Wagmeister|first=Elizabeth|date=August 29, 2016|magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|accessdate=29 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2017, [[Rumer Willis]] joined the third season of ''Empire'' in a recurring role.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2017/02/demi-moore-empire-recurring-season-3-season-4-fox-drama-series-1201927866/|title=Demi Moore Set To Recur On \u2018Empire\u2019|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|first=Denise|last=Petski|date=February 21, 2017|accessdate=February 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==== Jussie Smollett ====\n[[File:Jussie Smollett (26362136311).jpg|thumb|Smollett in 2016]]\nOn January 22, 2019, [[Jussie Smollett]] filed a police report about a threatening letter sent to Fox Studios, where ''Empire'' is filmed. According to Smollett, the letter contained \"threatening language\" and a powdery substance believed to be crushed-up [[Tylenol (brand)|Tylenol]].<ref name=\"abcnews.go.com\">{{Cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/US/timeline-alleged-jussie-smollett-attack/story?id=61124090|title=Timeline of the Jussie Smollett attack investigation|date=2019-02-21|website=ABC News|language=en|access-date=2019-03-01}}</ref> On January 29, 2019, Smollett reported that he was attacked by two men who shouted \"homophobic and racial slurs\" at him and then threw an \"unknown chemical substance\" on him. Smollett told police that they wrapped a rope around his neck, yelled \"[[Make America Great Again|MAGA]] country\",<ref name=\"goodmorningamerica.com\">{{Cite web|url=https://goodmorningamerica.com/culture/story/empire-star-brutally-attacked-hospitalized-hate-crime-60701735|title='Empire' star Jussie Smollett brutally attacked, hospitalized in possible hate crime|date=2019-01-31|website=ABC News|language=en|access-date=2019-03-01}}</ref> which references President [[Donald Trump]]'s \"Make America Great Again\" (MAGA) slogan.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://tsdr.uspto.gov/#caseNumber=85783371&caseType=SERIAL_NO&searchType=statusSearch|title=Trademark Status & Document Retrieval|website=tsdr.uspto.gov|access-date=2019-03-01}}</ref> Smollett was then hospitalized.<ref name=\"goodmorningamerica.com\"/>\n\nOn February 13, Chicago police arrested two \"persons of interest\". However, on February 14, 2019, it was revealed that police were investigating whether Smollett and the two men staged the attack because Smollett believed he was being written off ''Empire''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://abc7chicago.com/5138497/|title=Sources: Police investigating whether Smollett staged attack with help of others|date=2019-02-14|website=ABC7 Chicago|language=en|access-date=2019-03-01}}</ref> Interrogations revealed that both men, the Osundairo brothers, were allegedly paid off by Smollett to stage the attack.<ref name=\"abcnews.go.com\"/> On February 20, 2019, Smollett was indicted for filing a false police report.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/02/20/arts/television/jussie-smollett-attack-suspect.html|title=Accused of Faking Own Assault, Jussie Smollett Arrested on Felony Charge|last=Deb|first=Sopan|date=2019-02-20|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-03-01|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> He faces a maximum of three years in prison.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/02/20/arts/television/jussie-smollett-attack-suspect.html|title=Accused of Faking Own Assault, Jussie Smollett Arrested on Felony Charge|last=Deb|first=Sopan|date=2019-02-20|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-03-01|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nSubsequently, Smollett was removed from the last two episodes of the fifth season. In a written statement, the show's producers said that \"While these allegations are very disturbing, we are placing our trust in the legal system as the process plays... We are also aware of the effects of this process on the cast and crew members who work on our show and to avoid further disruption on set, we have decided to remove the role of 'Jamal' from the final two episodes of the season.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sunburynews.com/features/26287/character-removed-from-empire|title=Character removed from \u2018Empire\u2019 - Sunbury News|date=2019-02-28|website=www.sunburynews.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-01}}</ref>\n\nOn March 26, it was announced that the charges against Smollett had been dropped, although he remains under federal investigation regarding a hate letter that is believed to have been written by Smollett himself. The fate of Smollett's character 'Jamal' currently remains unclear.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://deadline.com/2019/03/jussie-smollett-criminal-charges-dropped-attorneys-1202582769/|title=Jussie Smollett Criminal Charges Dropped; State Says \"Appropriate Resolution,\" Family \"Thank God\" \u2013 Update|last=Petski, Patten|first=Denise, Dominic|magazine=Deadline|date=March 26, 2019|accessdate=March 28, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://deadline.com/2019/03/jussie-smollett-empire-future-series-renewal-criminal-charges-dropped-fox-1202583688/|title=Jussie Smollett Fallout Addles Actor\u2019s \u2018Empire\u2019 Future; Series Renewal Looks Likely|last=Patten|first=Dominic|magazine=Deadline|date=March 27, 2019|accessdate=March 28, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn April 30, 2019, it was announced that although Fox Entertainment had extended Smollett's contract for season six of ''Empire'', there were no plans for the character to appear during the season.<ref name=\"apnews\">{{cite web |title=Jussie Smollett will not return to 'Empire' for next season |url=https://www.apnews.com/b3276d9075aa437c859ed40ed2ec0661 |publisher=[[Associated Press|AP News]] |accessdate=May 22, 2019 |date=April 30, 2019}}</ref><ref>https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/empire-renewed-fox-jussie-smollett-unlikely-return-n1000416</ref>\n\nOn June 4, 2019, series co-creator Lee Daniels officially announced that Smollett would not be returning for the sixth and final season.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://deadline.com/2019/06/jussie-smollett-will-not-be-returning-to-empire-lee-daniels-says-1202627235/|title=Jussie Smollett \"Will Not Be Returning To Empire,\" Lee Daniels Says|last=Bennett, Patten|first=Anita, Dominic|magazine=Deadline|date=June 4, 2019|accessdate=June 5, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Music===\nAfter finding his lead actors, Lee Daniels set out to find a producer to craft the music for the series. Because he felt his own musical tastes and desires would be a little too dated for the show, Daniels consulted with people he thought could give him a little more insight, his children. At the urging of his son and daughter, Daniels contacted super producer [[Timbaland|Timothy \"Timbaland\" Mosley]], known for scoring hits with some of pop's biggest artists including [[Missy Elliott]], [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]], [[Brandy Norwood|Brandy]], [[Destiny's Child]], [[Justin Timberlake]], [[Jay-Z]], [[Nelly Furtado]], [[Ginuwine]], and [[Aaliyah]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.songfacts.com/category-songs_produced_by_timbaland.php|title=SONGS PRODUCED BY TIMBALAND|publisher=Songfacts.com|accessdate=January 28, 2015}}</ref>\n\nAs executive music Producer, Timbaland, co-songwriter/producer [[Jim Beanz]], and a team of other musical collaborators took their cues from the writing team, which gave them an idea of where the plot is headed, and craft songs to fit those themes. However, the musical aspect of the series is very reality based, unlike Fox's last musical series, ''[[Glee (TV series)|Glee]]'', performances come with the organic development of the characters as artists, much like the performances featured in the ABC prime-time country musical drama ''[[Nashville (2012 TV series)|Nashville]]''.<ref name=EWStack010715>{{cite web|url=http://insidetv.ew.com/2015/01/07/empire-fox-lee-daniels/|title='Empire': Inside Fox's ambitious, groundbreaking musical soap|first=Tim|last=Stack|date=January 7, 2015|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|publisher=[[Time Inc.]]|accessdate=January 7, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://alistarrecords.com/track/731526/what-the-dj-spins-from-empire?feature_id=157084&trackship_id=833644 |title=What the DJ Spins (Empire) |publisher=Alistar Records |access-date=June 24, 2015}}</ref>\n\nAny licensed songs and composer Fil Eisler's score are added after the episodes are filmed. The pilot itself consists of 12 songs.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2015/tv/features/timbaland-gives-lee-daniels-empire-hip-hop-cred-1201393126/|title=Timbaland Gives Lee Daniels' 'Empire' Hip-Hop Cred|first=Melinda|last=Newman|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]]|date=January 6, 2015|accessdate=January 7, 2015}}</ref> [[Columbia Records]] releases weekly soundtracks of ''Empire'' on the [[iTunes Store]], the same strategy used with ''Glee''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.inquisitr.com/1860247/empire-tv-show-on-fox-empire-soundtrack-music-soars-on-itunes-ratings-break-records/ |title=\u2018EMPIRE\u2019 TV SHOW ON FOX: \u2018EMPIRE\u2019 SOUNDTRACK MUSIC SOARS ON ITUNES, RATINGS BREAK RECORDS |last=Mooney |first=Paula |date=February 20, 2015|accessdate=March 24, 2017}}</ref> In May 2015, Fox announced that [[Ne-Yo]] and [[J.R. Rotem]] would write music for the show's second season, joining Timbaland.<ref name=\"Neyo2\"/> Timbaland left ''Empire'' after season 2, and were replaced for season 3 by [[Rodney \"Darkchild\" Jerkins]] and [[Esther Dean]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fuse.tv/2016/09/empire-timbaland-exit-ester-dean-rodney-jerkins-darkchild|title='EMPIRE' LOSES TIMBALAND, SIGNS ESTER DEAN & RODNEY 'DARKCHILD' JERKINS\n|first=Melinda|last=Newman|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]]|date=September 15, 2016|accessdate=March 24, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn September 8, 2015, Scott Hoying and Mitch Grassi from [[Pentatonix]] arranged a medley of songs from the first season of ''Empire'' and posted it on their shared YouTube comedy/music channel, [[Superfruit (web show)|Superfruit]]. The video was sponsored by the Fox Broadcasting Company.\n\n====Soundtracks====\n{{main|Empire discography}}\n[[Columbia Records]] released the official [[soundtrack]] of ''Empire''\u2019s first season on March 10, 2015.<ref name=\"Season 1\">{{cite web |url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/original-soundtrack-from-season/id966019045 |title=Original Soundtrack from Season 1 of Empire by Empire Cast |work=[[iTunes Store]] |publisher=[[Apple Inc.|Apple]] |accessdate=March 18, 2015}}</ref> The soundtrack consists of 11 songs and the deluxe version consists of 18 songs, all performed on the show. As of October 2015, the album has sold 439,000 total copies in the United States.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nielsen.com/us/en/insights/news/2015/a-sprawling-empire-how-foxs-hit-tv-show-affects-music.html |title=A SPRAWLING EMPIRE: HOW FOX'S HIT TV SHOW AFFECTS MUSIC |website=nielsen |date=September 23, 2015 |accessdate=October 10, 2015}}</ref> Additional releases have followed for subsequent seasons.\n\nFor [[Empire (season 6)|season 6]], four songs from the premiere episode were released in advance of the season, and two new songs will be released each week ahead of each new episode.<ref>{{cite web |title=Four Songs from EMPIRE Season 6 Premiere Available Now |url=https://www.broadwayworld.com/bwwtv/article/Four-Songs-from-EMPIRE-Season-6-Premiere-Available-Now-20190920 |website=Broadway World |accessdate=25 September 2019}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Soundtrack\n! scope=\"col\"| Release date\n! scope=\"col\"| Format(s)\n! scope=\"col\"| Label\n! scope=\"col\"| Edition(s)\n! scope=\"col\"| {{abbr|Ref.|References}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Empire: Original Soundtrack from Season 1|Season 1]]\n| March 10, 2015\n| {{flatlist|\n* [[Compact disc|CD]]\n* [[Music download|Digital download]]\n}}\n| rowspan=\"6\"| [[Columbia Records|Columbia]]\n| {{flatlist|\n*Standard\n*Deluxe\n}}\n| <ref name=\"Season 1\"/>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Season 1\n| September 11, 2015\n| Digital download\n| ''The Complete Season 1''\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=https://itun.es/gb/GinS9|title=iTunes \u2013 Music \u2013 Empire: The Complete Season 1 by Empire Cast|publisher=[[iTunes Store]]}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Empire: Original Soundtrack Season 2 Volume 1|Season 2 (Vol. 1)]]\n| November 20, 2015\n| rowspan=\"2\"| {{flatlist|\n* CD\n* Digital download\n}}\n| rowspan=\"2\"| {{flatlist|\n*Standard\n*Deluxe\n}}\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=https://itun.es/gb/25jZ-|title=iTunes \u2013 Music \u2013 Empire (Original Soundtrack from Season 2), Vol. 1 by Empire Cast|publisher=[[iTunes Store]] (GB)|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20151206232042/https://itun.es/gb/25jZ-|archivedate=2015-12-06|df=}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Empire: Original Soundtrack Season 2 Volume 2|Season 2 (Vol. 2)]]\n| April 29, 2016\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=https://itun.es/gb/JUIqbb|title=iTunes \u2013 Music \u2013 Empire (Original Soundtrack) [Season 2] [Deluxe] Vol. 2 by Empire Cast|publisher=[[iTunes Store]] (GB)}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Season 2\n| July 8, 2016\n| Digital download\n| ''The Complete Season 2''\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=https://itun.es/gb/0TFydb|title=iTunes \u2013 Music \u2013 Empire: The Complete Season 2 by Empire Cast|publisher=[[iTunes Store]]}}{{Dead link|date=August 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Empire: Original Soundtrack Season 3|Season 3]]\n| April 28, 2017\n| {{hlist|CD|Digital download}}\n| Standard\n| <ref>{{cite web|title=iTunes - Music - Empire: Original Soundtrack, Season 3 by Empire Cast|url=https://itun.es/gb/37JZib|publisher=[[iTunes Store]]}}{{Dead link|date=August 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Broadcast==\n''Empire'' was set to premiere in Australia on February 19, 2015 on [[Network Ten]];<ref>{{cite web|website=[[TV Tonight]]|first=David|last=Knox|title=Airdate: Empire|url=http://www.tvtonight.com.au/2015/01/airdate-empire-2.html|date=January 30, 2014|accessdate=January 30, 2015}}</ref> however, a week out from this date it was dumped from the schedule and pushed back. It ultimately premiered on March 1, 2015,<ref>{{cite web|website=[[TV Tonight]]|first=David|last=Knox|title=Update: Empire, Elementary.|url=http://www.tvtonight.com.au/2015/02/update-empire-elementary-update.html|date=February 12, 2015|accessdate=February 12, 2015}}</ref> to a disappointing 377,000 total viewers, although it fared better with viewers in younger demographics.<ref>{{cite web|website=[[TV Tonight]]|first=David|last=Knox|title=Empire music falls on younger ears|url=http://www.tvtonight.com.au/2015/03/empire-music-falls-on-younger-ears.html|date=March 2, 2015|accessdate=March 6, 2015}}</ref> The second season was broadcast on [[Eleven (TV channel)|Eleven]] from September 29, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|website=[[TV Tonight]]|first=David|last=Knox|url=http://www.tvtonight.com.au/2015/09/returning-empire.html|title=Returning: Empire |date=September 15, 2015|accessdate=September 25, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn Canada, the series was simulcast on [[Omni Television]] ([[CJMT-DT|Omni 2]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.omnitv.ca/on/en/shows/empire/ |title=Empire|publisher=omnitv.ca|accessdate=February 19, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.canoe.ca/rabbitears/television/building-an-empire-hit-fox-drama-series-gets-trial-run-on-city-in-addition-to-omni/|title=Building an Empire; Hit Fox drama series gets trial run on City, in addition to OMNI|accessdate=February 18, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150129044835/http://blogs.canoe.ca/rabbitears/television/building-an-empire-hit-fox-drama-series-gets-trial-run-on-city-in-addition-to-omni/|archive-date=January 29, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> The fourth episode and the season finale would also air on [[City (TV network)|City]], a sibling broadcast network.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chfi.com/2015/01/28/video-empire-on-city/|title=VIDEO \u2013 Empire on City|accessdate=February 2, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150202011738/http://www.chfi.com/2015/01/28/video-empire-on-city/|archive-date=February 2, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/television/2015/03/19/empire-ends-a-record-setting-first-season-with-176-million-viewers.html|title=Empire ends a record-setting first season with 17.6 million viewers |accessdate=July 21, 2015}}</ref> Sibling cable network [[FX (Canada)|FX Canada]] would also air a marathon of the show on March 14 and 15, 2015.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ca.hellomagazine.com/film/02015031314390/empire-s-jussie-smollett-on-his-inspiration-working-with-terrence-howard-and-the-queen-of-all-things-great/|title=Empire's Jussie Smollett on his inspiration, working with Terrence Howard and the 'queen of all things great'|accessdate=July 21, 2015}}</ref> The show moved to City starting in the 2015\u201316 season,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.channelcanada.com/canadian-channels/nets/citytv/citytvs-fall-2015-schedule-is-here|title=Citytv's Fall 2015 Schedule is here!|accessdate=July 21, 2015}}</ref> but was dropped from their lineup after the first half of the second season due to low ratings; Fox affiliates are widely available on pay television as well as over-the-air in some areas. [[Shomi]], a subscription streaming service co-owned by City's parent company [[Rogers Communications]], began to add new episodes following their U.S. premiere on Fox. A representative of the service stated that ''Empire'' was among its ten most popular programs.<ref name=\"cp-unwantedtv\">{{cite web|title=Unwanted broadcast TV shows proving major benefit to video streaming services|url=https://vancouversun.com/technology/empire+stop+airing+canadian+network+city+will+stream+shomi/11738034/story.html|publisher=Canadian Press|accessdate=April 28, 2016}}</ref>\n\n''Empire'' started broadcasting in the UK on [[E4 (TV channel)|E4]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2015/apr/07/lee-daniels-hip-hop-drama-empire-e4 |title=Lee Daniels hip-hop drama Empire heading to E4 |work=The Guardian |first=Ben |last=Beaumont-Thomas |date=April 7, 2015 |accessdate=April 7, 2015}}</ref> with the first episode airing on April 28, 2015.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nme.com/filmandtv/news/us-hip-hop-drama-empire-to-begin-on-e4-later-this-/376212 |title=US hip-hop drama 'Empire' to begin on E4 later this month |date=April 16, 2015 |work=[[NME]] |accessdate=April 30, 2015 }}</ref> [[5Star]] have since taken over the rights as of Season 4. The series premiered in [[India]] on [[STAR World Premiere|STAR World Premiere HD]] on April 24, 2015 (only in high-definition). Later, on July 14, 2015, Empire also premiered on [[FX (Asia)|FX India]] (both in standard and high definition) with the Season 1 finale airing on July 29, 2015. Empire premiered on June 24, 2015 in Germany on [[Pro Sieben]], with the Pilot reaching 930,000 viewers.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.quotenmeter.de/n/79081/primetime-check-mittwoch-24-juni-2015 |title=Primetime-Check: Mittwoch, 24. Juni 2015 |date=June 25, 2015 |work=Quotenmeter.de|accessdate=June 25, 2015 }}</ref> In Finland, the show premiered on [[Sub (TV channel)|Sub]] on December 2, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|title=Empire on vuoden tv-yll\u00e4tt\u00e4j\u00e4 Yhdysvalloissa \u2013 lukeutuu Michelle  Obaman suosikkeihin|url=http://www.mtv.fi/viihde/ohjelmat/empire/uutiset/artikkeli/empire-on-vuoden-tv-yllattaja-yhdysvalloissa-lukeutuu-michelle-obaman-suosikkeihin/5523708|website=[[MTV3]]|publisher=[[Bonnier Group|Bonnier]]|language=Finnish|accessdate=December 4, 2015|date=October 28, 2015}}</ref>\nIn South Africa, the show premiered on [[e.tv]] on February 3, 2016. In Serbia series start January 23, 2016 on Fox it aired Thursdays at 10pm.\n\nIn the United States, [[TV One (American TV channel)|TV One]] have the exclusive cable rerun rights.\n\n==Reception==\nIn 2016, a ''[[New York Times]]'' study of the 50 TV shows with the most [[Facebook Like]]s found that ''Empire'' \"is most popular in the [[Black Belt (geological formation)|Black Belt]] and in parts of the country with a high percentage of [[Native Americans in the United States|Native American]]s\".<ref name=\"katz20161227\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2016/12/26/upshot/duck-dynasty-vs-modern-family-television-maps.html |title=\u2018Duck Dynasty\u2019 vs. \u2018Modern Family\u2019: 50 Maps of the U.S. Cultural Divide |last=Katz |first=Josh |date=2016-12-27 |newspaper=The New York Times}}</ref>\n\n===Ratings===\n{{see also|List of Empire episodes#Ratings}}\n{{Television season ratings\n| link1            = Empire (s